##############################################################
#
#  Setup
#
#

Context("Numeric");
#given
$B = random(1.2,1.6,0.1);

#computation
$N = ceil(ln(1000)/ln($B));
$v = sqrt(2*9.8*($B**$N-1000));

#set tolerance
Context()->flags->set(
tolerance=>.02,
tolType=>'relative');

##############################################################
#
#  PGML 
#
#

BEGIN_PGML

A magical rubber ball has the incredible property that every time it bounces, instead of losing energy, it gains energy.
With each bounce, its energy is multiplied by [`$B`]. If the ball is dropped from a height of [`1 \: m`], find 
the number of bounces before it first reaches a height of [`1 \: km`]. 
Ignore air resistance and assume a constant [`g = 9.80 \: m/s^2`].

Number of bounces: [______]{"$N"}

Find the speed of the ball the first time it reaches a height of [`1 \: km`].

[`v =`] [______]{"$v"} [`m/s`]

END_PGML

